	<h1>Judith's pick: Early July 2013</h1>

	<h2 class="post-subtitle">
					18/07/2013
						- 												
	</h2>

	
		    <div class="attribute-long">
		
<p>Here a list of recent developments in agricultural research. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Postharvest losses of dry grains in North Western Benin</b></p><p>A quantitative survey investigates in more depth the issue of storage losses, their causes and means of improving food conservation in the long term. &nbsp;Key issues are the poor availability of storage facilities and suitable packaging material and the lack of pest management knowledge. The document also explores the management methods the country’s extension system is promoting.</p><p><a href="http://www.sdc-foodsecurity.ch/en/media/briefs/afs_brief_no4_en.pdf" target="_self">http://www.sdc-foodsecurity.ch/en/media/briefs/afs_brief_no4_en.pdf</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Conservation agriculture and micro-dosing in Zimbabwe</b></p><p>By adopting conservation agriculture (CA) practices and/or micro-dosing of fertiliser, this joint ICRISAT/EIARD brief explains how small-scale farming households in Zimbabwe have improved and stabilised yields and conserved moisture and built soil health.</p><p><a href="http://eiard.org/media/uploads/File/Case%20studies/2013_SDC%20funded/ICRISAT%20-%20Conservation%20agriculture%20and%20micro-dosing%20in%20Zimbabwe.pdf" target="_self">http://eiard.org/media/uploads/File/Case%20studies/2013_SDC%20funded/ICRISAT%20-%20Conservation%20agriculture%20and%20micro-dosing%20in%20Zimbabwe.pdf</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Climate resilient root-crops distributed in Fiji</b></p><p>Three salt-tolerant varieties of dalo (taro), cassava and kumala (sweet potato) that can thrive in Fiji’s high-salt water table areas have been introduced to several of the island’s rural villages. The regions in which the root crops are distributed are suffering from poor, man-made drainage system that exacerbates the effects of climate change.</p><p><a href="http://www.islandsbusiness.com/news/fiji/1663/climate-resilient-root-crops-trialed-in-fiji/" target="_self">http://www.islandsbusiness.com/news/fiji/1663/climate-resilient-root-crops-trialed-in-fiji/</a></p><p><b>-&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Turning over a new leaf in plant genomics</b></p><p>A special issue of <i>Genome Biology</i>, published early July 2013, highlights current top plant research with articles on crops (sorghum, maize, barley, cocoa, wheat, vegetables), micro-organisms (plant-microbe interactions, root hairs), methods and techniques (cloning, mapping-by-sequencing), etc. This special issue provides a collection of reviews, opinions and presentations of current scientific work, the vast majority are free to access.</p><p>&nbsp;<a href="http://genomebiology.com/content/14/6" target="_self">http://genomebiology.com/content/14/6</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Launch of a new African Plant Breeding Academy</b></p><p>The Academy aims to sequence the genomes of 96 indigenous orphan crops that are important for African diets (African eggplant, potato, cocoyam, Ethiopian mustard, as well as cassava, cacao, millet, sorghum and legumes, among others). Participating African plant breeders will be trained in the most advanced theory and technologies for plant breeding, quantitative genetics, statistics and experimental design.</p><p><a href="http://www.news.ucdavis.edu/search/news_detail.lasso?id=10632" target="_self">http://www.news.ucdavis.edu/search/news_detail.lasso?id=10632</a></p><p><b>-&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Opportunities and challenges for using crop genetic improvement technologies for sustainable agriculture </b></p><p>The European Academies Science Advisory Council (EASAC) reports on the opportunities and challenges in using plant genetic resources in new or improved breeding approaches, for example by using marker-assisted selection of desired traits. EASAC explores some of the policy, scientific and technological issues associated with the genetic modification of crops; in order to address European policy inconsistencies around this technology.</p><p><a href="http://www.easac.eu/home/reports-and-statements/detail-view/article/planting-the.html" target="_self">http://www.easac.eu/home/reports-and-statements/detail-view/article/planting-the.html</a></p><p><b>- &nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Tomato fruits: a good target for iodine biofortification</b></p><p>This experiment evaluated the possibility of biofortifying tomato fruits with iodine. Results showed that the use of iodized salts induced a significant increase in the fruit’s iodine content in doses that did not affect plant growth and development. Tomato proved to be particularly suitable crop for iodine biofortification programmes.</p><p><a href="http://www.frontiersin.org/Plant_Physiology/10.3389/fpls.2013.00205/abstract" target="_self">http://www.frontiersin.org/Plant_Physiology/10.3389/fpls.2013.00205/abstract</a></p><p><i>Note: The iodine problem affects only certain regions of the world. From the PLOS ONE article below (see figure 2):</i></p><p><i>“The pattern and magnitude of iodine deficiency did not conform to that of other micronutrients. The greatest proportions of children with iodine deficiency were in the Eastern Mediterranean (46.6%), European (44.2%), and African (40.4%) regions.”</i></p><p><i>Some foods are naturally rich in iodine: beans, potatoes (with skin), gray (rock) salt, sea vegetables (kelp), yoghurt.</i></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action</b></p><p>Indices and maps of global hidden hunger are being developed to help prioritise programme assistance and to serve as an evidence-based global advocacy tool. This research proposes two types of hidden hunger indices and maps. The study demonstrates how these indices and maps provide crucial data for tackling global multiple micronutrient deficiencies and could help to scale up effective nutrition interventions.</p><p><a href="http://www.plosone.org/article/info:doi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0067860" target="_self">http://www.plosone.org/article/info:doi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0067860</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Global crop exposure to high temperatures in the reproductive period: historical trends and future projections</b></p><p>Regardless of the impact of other global change factors (such as increasing atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub>), the researchers believe that reproductive extreme heat exposure will pose risks for global crop production. Adaptive measures such as changes in sowing dates, crop and variety switching, expansion of irrigation, and agricultural expansion into cooler areas have to be considered when drafting agricultural policy. These results show the importance of specialised data and up-to-date climate models when planning for agricultural adaptation.</p><p><a href="http://foodsecurity.stanford.edu/publications/global_crop_exposure_to_critical_high_temperatures_in_the_reproductive_period_historical_trends_and_future_projections/" target="_self">http://foodsecurity.stanford.edu/publications/global_crop_exposure_to_critical_high_temperatures_in_the_reproductive_period_historical_trends_and_future_projections/</a></p><p>-&nbsp;</p><p><b>Farmer’s choice of seeds in four EU countries under different levels of GM crop adoption</b></p><p>Researchers looked into the agricultural seed catalogues available to farmers in countries with different degrees of GM crop adoption (Austria, Germany, Spain, and Switzerland). The results show that, between 1995 and 2011, in the countries that did not adopt GM crop, actual restrictions and regulations of GM crops have not decreased seed choices/cultivar availability for farmers. In Spain, which has adopted GM maize, the seed market was more concentrated with fewer differentiated cultivars on offer: the overall number of maize cultivars declined.</p><p><a href="http://www.enveurope.com/content/25/1/12/abstract" target="_self">http://www.enveurope.com/content/25/1/12/abstract</a></p><p><i>Note: There is a push for the EU to open up the GM restrictions. Is this one of the reasons they may want to reflect on in future decision-making?</i></p><p><b>- &nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Realising Farmers' Rights to Crop Genetic Resources: Success Stories and Best Practices </b></p><p>This book provides decision-makers and practitioners with a conceptual framework for understanding ‘Farmers’ Rights’ in the context of crop genetic resources (CGR) sharing. It compiles success stories (from Ethiopia, Mali and Zimbabwe, among others) showing how each of the elements of Farmers' Rights to CGR can be realised in practice. Substantial achievements have been made on several important fronts: the rights of farmers to save, use, exchange and sell farm-saved seed; the protection of traditional knowledge; benefit-sharing; and participation in decision-making.</p><p><a href="http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415643849/#description" target="_self">http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415643849/#description</a></p><p><b>-</b></p><p><b>Expert comments on ‘Sustainable Intensification in Agriculture’ </b></p><p>Following the release last year of the report on ‘Sustainable Intensification in Agriculture’ by the Food Climate Research Network (FCRN) and the Oxford Martin Programme on the Future of Food, around 30 experts in this field, from academic, governmental, NGO and industrial organisations, were asked to comment on the report. These comments have all been compiled into a report which can be downloaded here:</p><p><a href="http://www.fcrn.org.uk/sites/default/files/sustainable_intensification_comments.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fcrn.org.uk/sites/default/files/sustainable_intensification_comments.pdf</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://www.futureoffood.ox.ac.uk/news/sustainable-intensification-agriculture-premises-and-policies" target="_self">http://www.futureoffood.ox.ac.uk/news/sustainable-intensification-agriculture-premises-and-policies</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><a href="http://phys.org/news/2013-07-food-sustainably.html" target="_self">http://phys.org/news/2013-07-food-sustainably.html</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>-</p><p><b>Two new reports by the High Level Panel of Experts on Food Security and Nutrition (HLPE)</b></p><p>‘Biofuels and food security’ and ‘Investing in smallholder agriculture for food security’ have been published in June 2013. Recommendations on future public policies regarding biofuel production and on investment strategies that include smallholders are drafted in the respective HLPE reports.</p><p><a href="http://www.fao.org/cfs/cfs-hlpe/en/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/cfs/cfs-hlpe/en/</a></p><p><b>-</b></p><p><b>Results and innovations from transnational research partnerships</b></p><p>The objective of this research fair was to enable exchange and dialogue between science, policy, and practice for securing global public goods in the context of sustainable development. From this page, download presentations by key staff of participating organisations on topics such as ‘Getting research and innovation into policy and practice’.</p><p><a href="http://www.kfpe.ch/key_activities/workshops/research-Fair.php" target="_self">http://www.kfpe.ch/key_activities/workshops/research-Fair.php</a></p><p><b>-</b></p><p><b>Documentation of the symposium on Rural Advisory Services</b></p><p>The GIZ Sector Project Sustainable Agriculture organised this symposium on Rural Advisory Services (RAS), early 2013. The documentation includes: 1) a global status report of RAS and five key areas for mobilisation; 2) Practice review lessons learned from implementation; 3) a summary of the panel discussion.</p><p><a href="http://www.sdc-foodsecurity.ch/en/Home/News_in_A_RD/media/Documentation%20Symposium%20Rural%20Advisory%20Services.pdf" target="_self">http://www.sdc-foodsecurity.ch/en/Home/News_in_A_RD/media/Documentation%20Symposium%20Rural%20Advisory%20Services.pdf</a></p><p><b>-</b></p><p><b>European manufacturers to halve food waste, Australian research quantifies food waste</b></p><p>Representatives from Europe’s food supply chains have committed their organisations to reducing edible food waste. A life-cycle approach is being developed for critical products.</p><p>In Australia, a study, titled ‘The role of packaging in minimising food waste in the supply chain of the future’, focused on where and why food waste occurs both along the fresh and processed food supply. The research identifies opportunities for industry to address food waste through innovative and sustainable packaging.</p><p><a href="http://www.ausfoodnews.com.au/2013/07/01/european-manufacturers-to-halve-food-waste-australian-research-quantifies-food-waste.html" target="_self">http://www.ausfoodnews.com.au/2013/07/01/european-manufacturers-to-halve-food-waste-australian-research-quantifies-food-waste.html</a></p><p><b>-</b></p><p><b>New packaging for Tonga’s agriculture export products</b></p><p>The Pacific Horticultural and Agricultural Market Access Project (PHAMA) developed new packaging material (retail plastic bags) and design (of label stickers) for Tonga’s frozen root crop (cassava) products. Primarily meant to help producers meet market standards and compliance requirements in the New Zealand and Australian markets, the new labelling may well strengthen the competitive advantage of Tonga’s agricultural export products. Four exporting companies have been selected to conduct the trial run of the packaging.</p><p><a href="http://www.pacifictradeinvest.com/wp/?p=5086" target="_self">http://www.pacifictradeinvest.com/wp/?p=5086</a></p><p>-</p><p><b>Climate models: more questions than answers</b></p><p>Sonja Vermeulen of CGIAR CCAFS discusses the pertinence of current climate models, citing recent research. Sonja explains why models are poor at representing inter-annual variability and why they perform much better for some regions and some crops than for others. She argues that the ’models’ ability to represent climate is improving [...].&nbsp; However, if models are to advance sufficiently to permit assessments of future crop yields before today’s young scientists have retired, we need major breakthroughs in modelling approaches, not just linear improvements.’</p><p><a href="http://ccafs.cgiar.org/blog/climate-models-more-questions-answers" target="_self">http://ccafs.cgiar.org/blog/climate-models-more-questions-answers</a></p><p>-</p><p><b>Ideas competition: ‘Fight Food Losses and Food Waste’</b></p><p>Deadline: 30 August 2013</p><p>The Swiss National FAO Committee has launched a student competition aiming to develop innovative ideas on how to fight food waste in Switzerland and postharvest losses in developing countries. The best ideas will be awarded at a public event on the eve of World Food Day 2013.</p><p><a href="http://ourcommonfood.ch/" target="_self">http://ourcommonfood.ch/</a></p><p>-</p><p>More to come in the next newsletter.</p>
	    </div>
	
	
	
